Usage: cylc remove [OPTIONS] ID ... 

Remove one or more task instances from a running workflow.

This command can operate on multiple workflows, globs may also be used:
    Multiple Workflows:
        [2m# Operate on two workflows[0m
        workflow-1 workflow-2

    Globs (note: globs should be quoted):
        [2m# Match all workflows[0m
        '*'

        [2m# Match the workflows foo-1, foo-2[0m
        'foo-[12]'

    See `cylc help id` for more details.

This command can operate on multiple tasks, globs and selectors may
be used:
    Multiple Tasks:
        [2m# Operate on two tasks[0m
        workflow //cycle-1/task-1 //cycle-2/task-2

    Globs (note: globs should be quoted and only match active tasks):
        [2m# Match any the active task "foo" in all cycles[0m
        '//*/foo'

        [2m# Match the tasks "foo-1" and "foo-2"[0m
        '//*/foo-[12]'

    Selectors (note: selectors only match active tasks):
        [2m# match all failed tasks in cycle "1"[0m
        //1:failed

    See `cylc help id` for more details.


Arguments:
   ID ...               Cycle/Family/Task ID(s)

Options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  -q, --quiet           Decrease verbosity.
  -v, --verbose         Increase Verbosity
  --debug               Equivalent to -v -v
  --no-timestamp        Don't timestamp logged messages.
  --color=WHEN, --color=WHEN
                        When to use color/bold text in terminal output.
                        Options are 'never', 'auto' and 'always'.
  --comms-timeout=SEC   Set a timeout for network connections to the running
                        workflow. The default is no timeout. For task
                        messaging connections see site/user config file
                        documentation.
